The Nottingham East Labour Party said in a statement on Friday: “We want the meetings to be inclusive and productive.”
Most of the Friday evening meetings of the General Committee in my eight years as a local Member of Parliament from Labour were just that.
Unfortunately, many meetings today have a completely different tone, and the promise of a “more friendly, more soft” policy has long been forgotten, if it was ever implemented at all.
It is becoming increasingly clear that different views are not allowed in the Labour Party, and each opinion is assessed from the standpoint of whether it is acceptable to the leadership of the party.
It started shortly after Jeremy became a leader. Colleagues with whom, as it seemed to me earlier, I had similar political views, began to expect that I would turn 180 degrees and accept positions that I would never agree with, be it national security or the only one.
Whenever I speak in public — and it doesn’t matter what I say — this is followed by a tirade of attacks on social media with calls for withdrawal, condemnation of the center’s policies, I’m told I shouldn’t be in the Labour Party.
And it’s not just my experience.
I know that I have been more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me are usually political.
I am fascinated by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who face daily streams of sexist or racist attacks, but never give up.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is that levels of abuse have become the norm.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should nurture a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer such a broad church, and with every movement of “distrust” or change in the rules of selection, the party narrows down.
Over the past two years, I have been given a lot of advice. I have been asked not to stand out, not to speak out so loudly that “everything was fine” with me.
But that’s not why I came into politics.
I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a schoolchild, because because of the lack of attention from the Thatcher government, my high school class literally collapsed, and since then I have been striving to improve the quality of public services for those who need them most, be it a local councillor or a government minister.
I have never hid my politics, including in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East was embarrassed by my political views and disagreements with the current leadership.
For those who contributed to Friday’s events, I want to say only one thing: in a situation where the country is moving toward Brexit that will harm households, businesses and public services, I don’t understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
In fact, I have another message, but not for the Nottingham Momentum, but for my constituents, as members of the Labour Party, no: I am proud that I serve you, and I promise that there are no threats to withdraw me from you and no political advantage.
