John Edward: Knowledge of languages is mandatory for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland maintain high standards of learning, and in 2018, excellent exam results were again obtained, complemented by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other fields.
These schools, which have more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, are represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SNCS) and are committed to providing the best possible service for pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, as well as to make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a person in a language he understands, he perceives it with his mind.
If you speak to her in her native language, she perceives it with her heart.”
It’s a powerful reminder that we can’t just use English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the latest results of the exams this year, we see that in independent schools, languages lead in the rankings of the subjects with the best scores.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received a higher A score.
The data collected at 74 schools in the SNSH showed that 72% of students received a higher grade A from Chinese, and another 72% of those who learn German, 69% of those who learn French, and 63% of those who learn Spanish also received an A.
This indicates that independent schools in Scotland consider foreign languages to be vital skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Now languages as a subject of choice are taught in the same way as NTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), within the framework of independent school programs and in other institutions.
A survey conducted by the British Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17% of the reasons employers cannot close vacancies are due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more promising positions require knowledge of languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if someone has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future, because it is a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who speaks several languages an advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to support the conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15%).
That’s why investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, especially the languages of developing countries, will provide children with a better chance of finding a full-time job.
In Scotland, each school will learn its own language.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK from the perspective of 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests in independent schools, you will always be able to choose several languages to study them with qualified teachers.
Scottish independent schools are trying to create an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed, regardless of what prepares them for the future.
Now there is no denying that in the international business environment languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be considered “skills of international communication”.
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, diversity, and excellence to Scottish youth.
You have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
