North Korea says it will “in no way” disarm unilaterally without trust.
North Korea’s foreign minister said on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions deepens distrust of the United States, and that under such circumstances the country will not be able to give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual UN General Assembly last year that North Korea had taken “substantial goodwill measures” such as the cessation of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear test site and the commitment not to distribute nuclear weapons.
“However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
And although Ri repeated familiar complaints from North Korea about Washington’s opposition to the “stage-by-stage” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea will be rewarded for gradual steps, his statement was important in the fact that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization.
Ree referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the current US president and the leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim called for work on "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" and Trump promised security guarantees.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first abandon nuclear weapons.
Washington is also resisting calls to weaken tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal forcibly, and even denies the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“To think that sanctions can put us on our knees is an impossible dream for those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ree did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader emphasized at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If South Korea were the party to the denuclearization issue, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have gone that way."
Despite this, the tone of Ri’s speech was sharply different from last year’s when he told the General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” who wants to do it himself.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said much more would need to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump remarked that he did not set a time frame for this: “It will take two years, three years, or five months — it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of the Security Council’s sanctions must continue vigorously and steadfastly until we see complete, final, confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in order to block the financing of Pyongyang's nuclear programs and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was unsuccessful.
He left Pyongyang in July and commented that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea condemned him for "gangster demands".
During a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to dismantle the missile complex, as well as the nuclear complex, if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
He said that, according to Kim, he needs "appropriate measures" are guarantees of security that Trump promised in Singapore, and steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has provided all of its students with more sleep. This is an attempt to combat the growing culture of steep learning all night after a caffeine filling.
The professor found that world’s number one university students are often uneducated when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chassler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first such course in the United States.
He decided to start the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end, a girl approached him and said, “Why am I being told this now, in my last class?”
“She said that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” said a lecturer at The Telegraph.
In the course, which was first introduced this year, students are explained the basics of how good sleep habits help to achieve academic and sporting results, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of medical services at the university, said the university decided to introduce a course after it was found that students were severely sleep deprived for a week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a dormitory room where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, gymnasts and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the impact of sleep deficiency on sports performance, and the importance of sleep-related routines.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Next, the campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know this won’t change the behavior of students instantly.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” Professor Chassler added.
A culture of pride for “insomnia all night” still exists, he added, and also noted that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is growing.
Adequate sleep of good quality should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, even with a set of excess weight, as sleep deprivation translates the brain into a mode of hunger that causes constant physical hunger, he said.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chassler develop a course after enrolling in one of his other courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that course opened his eyes and inspired him to create a new course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to appeal to all postgraduate students with a request to undergo a similar study program before coming to a competitive institution.
Professor Chassler recommends that students put a reminder to go to bed and set an alarm and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” that is emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps and can disrupt the circadian rhythm, leading to problems.
