HIV/AIDS: China reports a sharp increase of 14% in the number of new cases of the disease
In China, a sharp increase of 14% in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS was reported.
According to the representatives of the health authorities, there are more than 820,000 patients in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases of the disease were reported.
In most cases, the disease was sexually transmitted, indicating a change in the past trend.
For a long time, in some regions of China, HIV spread rapidly through infected blood during transfusions.
However, according to official health officials at a conference in Yunnan province, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has dropped to almost zero.
However, compared to the previous year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV over time is a serious problem for the Chinese LGBT community.
The decriminalization of homosexuality in China took place in 1997, but the LGBT community often suffers from discrimination.
According to studies, 70-90% of men who have sex with other men later marry women because of the dominance of conservative values in the country.
The transmission of the disease in most cases occurs as a result of improper use of protective measures during sexual contact.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has pledged to provide free access to HIV medicines, seeing this as a way to partially solve the problem.
