World Internet Inventor Plans to Launch ‘New Internet’ to Create Competition between Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the global Internet, launches a new startup to create competition from Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is developing an open source platform Solid, the idea of which belongs to Berners-Lee.
With the Solid platform, users will be able to choose where to store data and who to give access to this or that information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of Inrupt was “world domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he said of the startup.
This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology, which will allow users to create a "personal online data store" or POD.
It can store contact lists, current affairs lists, calendar, audio library and other tools for your own use and work.
It’s like using Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify in one browser at the same time.
A unique feature of this personal online data repository is that it fully meets the needs of the user who can access any information.
The company calls it “expanding personal capabilities with data.”
According to Inrupt CEO John Bruce, the company aims to leverage resources, processes and relevant skills to make the Solid platform accessible to everyone.
Currently, the company consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired from IBM, several staffed developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own standalone applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not in talks with Facebook and Google about whether to make a full replacement when all of their business models undergo radical changes in a short period of time.
“We don’t ask for their permission.”
In a Saturday post on Medium, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s mission is “to provide commercial energy and ecosystems and to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network created on the basis of the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by founding the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential figure in the debate over net neutrality.
Even during the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee remained the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, The Web Foundation, and the Open Data Institute.
“I am very optimistic about the next era of network development,” Berners-Lee added.
