The only representative of the Anglican Church who received the Order of the Cross of Victoria for his participation in hostilities during the First World War is honored in his hometown 100 years later.
Lt. Col. Rev. Bernard Vann received an award for his participation in the attack under Bellangis and Leocure on September 29, 1918.
However, he was killed by a sniper bullet four days later and never knew he had received Britain’s highest military award.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unearthed a memorial stone during a parade in the town of Rushden, Northamptonshire.
