According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lt. Col. Vann moved his battalion through the Saint-Cathen Canal "through a very thick fog and under the dense fire of field guns and machine guns".
Later, he hurried to the edge of the fire and with "desperate courage" led the line forward, before which one broke into the field gun and destroyed three guns of the enemy unit.
Lieutenant Colonel Vanna was shot dead by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the war ended.
The 72-year-old Michael Vann said his grandfather had done something he himself would never have been able to repeat and that he deserved to be respected.
He and his brother Dr. James Vann put on the wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vanne said he was "very proud to be part of this parade" and added that "the courage of a true hero demonstrates the respect that so many people show him."
