The National Trust will observe the secret life of bats
A new study, which is being conducted on land in the Scottish Highlands, aims to establish how bats use the landscape in search of food.
Scientists hope that the obtained data will help shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals in order to take measures to preserve them in the future.
In the gardens of Inver in Western Ross, scientists of the National Trust of Scotland will observe such species as the dwarf netopyr and the pygmy netopyr, as well as the ears of the common and watery nightingale.
Special registrars will be placed in strategic locations on the land to observe the behavior of bats during the season.
Employees and volunteers of the National Trust of Scotland will also conduct mobile research using manual detectors.
Expert analysis of all recorded sounds will help to determine the frequency and belonging of bat screams.
It is then planned to develop a detailed map of the animals' habitat and prepare a report to link the behavior of the animals to their habitat.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at Scotland’s National Trust, hopes the findings will help determine which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to assess the effectiveness of environmental care measures (e.g. meadow formation) and identify optimal forest conservation methods for bats and other related species.
Over the past century, bat populations have declined significantly in Scotland and the United Kingdom.
They are threatened by active construction and development of territories, which deprives them of nesting places.
Other negative factors include wind installations and lighting, glue paper for flies, chemical processing of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
They are not actually blind.
However, because of hunting at night, the ears are more effective in helping them catch prey than the eyes.
They use a complex echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles in the flight path.
Scotland’s National Trust, which has more than 270 historic buildings, 38 special-purpose gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bat problems very seriously.
Ten specially trained experts regularly conduct research, inspections of nesting sites and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization’s efforts even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland. It is located on the territory of the Trivets site in the Dumfries and Galloway area. Eight of the ten species of bats that live in Scotland have been found there.
David Thompson, the manager of the premises, says that this is the perfect place for them.
"On the territory of the site Triv excellent conditions for bats," he assures.
"There are old buildings, many giant trees and other favorable living conditions.
However, we still need to learn a lot about bats. Thanks to the research we are doing here and elsewhere, we will be able to learn more about what they need for prosperity."
He insists that it is very important to check the territory for bats before carrying out any technical work, because the unintentional destruction of one nesting place for breeding young can kill up to 400 females with infants, which is likely to cause the destruction of the entire local popu.
Dogs and their nests are protected by law. Animals are forbidden to kill, torture or disturb.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Flea Conservation Centre, called on the public to join the organization's efforts.
She said: "We still need to know a lot about our bats. We have not yet revealed the characteristic features of the populations of many species."
